<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<task id="013" project="code-quality-and-assurance-r2">
  <metadata>
    <title>Migrate IDataverseService Consumers to Narrow Interfaces</title>
    <phase>2: Backend Structural Decomposition</phase>
    <status>pending</status>
    <estimated-hours>4</estimated-hours>
    <dependencies>010, 011, 012</dependencies>
    <blocks>014</blocks>
    <tags>refactoring, dotnet, bff-api</tags>
  </metadata>

  <prompt>
    After IDataverseService has been segregated into 9 narrow interfaces (task 012) and the God
    classes have been decomposed (tasks 010 and 011), migrate every service that currently injects
    IDataverseService to instead inject the narrowest applicable interface — or multiple narrow
    interfaces if the service genuinely uses methods from more than one domain. Register each
    narrow interface in the relevant DI module so that the container can resolve it.
  </prompt>

  <role>Senior .NET developer specializing in SOLID principles and service decomposition</role>

  <goal>
    Every consumer in src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/ injects only the interface(s) that
    cover the Dataverse methods it actually calls. No service injects IDataverseService unless it
    uses methods from 4 or more domain groups (genuine orchestrators). Narrow interfaces are
    registered in DI modules. dotnet build and dotnet test both pass.
  </goal>

  <context>
    <background>
      Task 012 created 9 narrow interfaces and made IDataverseService a composite. However, all
      existing consumers still inject IDataverseService (the full 63-method composite). This task
      completes the ISP migration by updating each consumer's constructor to depend only on the
      interface(s) matching the methods it actually calls. This reduces coupling, simplifies mock
      setup in tests, and makes the dependency graph legible. The newly extracted services from
      tasks 010 and 011 (OfficeDocumentPersistence, AnalysisDocumentLoader, etc.) should already
      use narrow interfaces; verify them first as a reference pattern before migrating the older
      services.
    </background>
    <relevant-files>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/ (modify — all services injecting IDataverseService)</file>
      <file>src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/DI/ (modify — register narrow interfaces per module)</file>
      <file>src/server/shared/Spaarke.Dataverse/ (read — reference the 9 narrow interface definitions)</file>
    </relevant-files>
  </context>

  <constraints>
    <constraint source="ADR-010">
      Register narrow interfaces in DI by resolving them from the existing IDataverseService
      registration. The recommended pattern is:
        services.AddScoped&lt;IDocumentDataverseService&gt;(sp =&gt; sp.GetRequiredService&lt;IDataverseService&gt;());
      This avoids registering a second concrete instance. Total non-framework DI registrations
      across the solution must remain at or below 15; count only registrations of new types, not
      forwarding delegates.
    </constraint>
  </constraints>

  <knowledge>
    <files>
      <file>.claude/adr/ADR-010.md</file>
    </files>
  </knowledge>

  <steps>
    <step order="1">
      Grep for all files in src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/ that reference IDataverseService in a
      constructor parameter or field declaration. Produce a list of all consumers. Include the
      newly created services from tasks 010 and 011 in this list so they can be verified too.
    </step>
    <step order="2">
      For each consumer, read the class and list every IDataverseService method it calls. Map
      those calls to the 9 narrow interfaces created in task 012. Record the mapping as a table:
        Service | Methods Called | Narrow Interface(s) Required
      This mapping drives all subsequent steps and must be completed before any code changes.
    </step>
    <step order="3">
      Starting with the services extracted in tasks 010 and 011 (OfficeDocumentPersistence,
      AnalysisDocumentLoader, AnalysisResultPersistence), verify they already use narrow
      interfaces. If not, update them first as a reference implementation.
    </step>
    <step order="4">
      Migrate each remaining consumer one at a time:
      (a) Update the constructor parameter type from IDataverseService to the narrowest
          applicable interface(s).
      (b) Update the private field declaration to match.
      (c) If the service uses methods from 2+ domains, inject each required narrow interface as
          a separate constructor parameter.
      (d) Run dotnet build after each individual service update — do not batch multiple services
          and fix errors in bulk.
    </step>
    <step order="5">
      For any service that uses methods from 4 or more domain groups, leave it injecting
      IDataverseService (the composite) and add a comment explaining why the broad dependency
      is justified.
    </step>
    <step order="6">
      Register each narrow interface used by at least one consumer in the appropriate DI module
      using the forwarding pattern:
        services.AddScoped&lt;IDocumentDataverseService&gt;(sp =&gt; sp.GetRequiredService&lt;IDataverseService&gt;());
      Add these registrations to the module that owns the consumer service.
    </step>
    <step order="7">
      Run dotnet build from the repository root — verify zero errors across the entire solution.
    </step>
    <step order="8">
      Run dotnet test — verify all existing tests pass. If any tests fail because mock setup
      now requires a different interface type, update the test mocks to use the narrow interface.
      Do not change test behavior or skip assertions.
    </step>
    <step order="9">
      Update projects/code-quality-and-assurance-r2/tasks/TASK-INDEX.md — mark task 013 complete.
    </step>
  </steps>

  <outputs>
    <output type="file">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Services/ (multiple modified consumer files)</output>
    <output type="file">src/server/api/Sprk.Bff.Api/Infrastructure/DI/ (modified DI modules with narrow interface registrations)</output>
  </outputs>

  <acceptance-criteria>
    <criterion>Every consumer service injects only the interface(s) corresponding to the Dataverse methods it actually calls</criterion>
    <criterion>No service injects IDataverseService unless it uses methods from 4 or more domain groups, with a justifying comment</criterion>
    <criterion>Narrow interfaces used by consumers are registered in the appropriate DI modules using the forwarding pattern</criterion>
    <criterion>dotnet build passes with zero errors across the entire solution</criterion>
    <criterion>dotnet test passes — all existing tests remain green and no assertions are weakened</criterion>
  </acceptance-criteria>
</task>
